6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Binance calculates funding rates every 8 hours using a traditional premium index based on perpetual-spot price differences across their deep order books. Bluefin updates funding rates hourly on Sui, creating more frequent arbitrage opportunities but with smaller position adjustments. Binance's deeper liquidity typically results in more stable funding rates, while Bluefin's hourly updates can create volatile rate swings during market stress. The shorter interval on Bluefin allows for more responsive rate corrections but requires active position management."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which platform offers better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"Binance provides more stable, predictable funding rates due to deeper liquidity, while Bluefin's hourly updates create more frequent but potentially volatile arbitrage windows. Binance suits larger positions, Bluefin favors active smaller strategies."},{"question":"How do the funding rate calculation methods differ?","answer":"Binance uses 8-hour intervals with traditional premium indexing across deep order books. Bluefin calculates rates hourly on Sui blockchain with potentially more volatile adjustments due to lower liquidity and newer infrastructure."},{"question":"What are the main risks comparing these platforms?","answer":"Binance faces regulatory uncertainty and centralized custody risks despite strong infrastructure. Bluefin carries smart contract risks, limited liquidity for large positions, and early-stage Sui ecosystem uncertainties."},{"question":"Which platform is better for institutional funding strategies?","answer":"Binance clearly leads for institutional use with deeper liquidity, proven infrastructure, and substantial insurance funds. Bluefin's limited pairs and lower volume make it unsuitable for large institutional funding strategies currently."}]}]
